That said, I'll point out some strats that might be usable for the team.
We have the full line-up this time, so I'm expecting some level of crazy plays.
Banshee, Ghoul, VD, Medium and Necro I see.
And I'm starting out as an Enchanted Ghoul.
So we're tilted towards intel in general.
Lemme just list out who the team members are role-wise.
From what I gather, Wesley = Bewaker, Mayor = Phyton and Oz = Hannah.
Pleasantries will have to wait for now.
Anyways, village is planning for a D3 intel claim. That means that the zombie shouldn't claim seer tomorrow. I suppose it might be an issue for us.
Main issue with the current und games is that village tends to use previous und setups as a baseline to see whether role claims are believable or not. Seer claims are out of the window in general.
There's literally been a seer only once in this series.
Ideal situayion for us is to utilise necro with a "throw a teammate under the bus" combo.
This is something that's been done before, so it is a fairly lethal combo.
Baseline idea is this: One of us comes out as an intel role and implicates another person into a lynch, then our necro revives that person the same night.
Roles that are optimal for the scapegoat are: Ghoul.
Considering my lack of presence on D2, I'm a perfect scapegoat as well.

Why the other roles are not good to be scapegoated? Because Necro is the key to the plan, the VD is our only constant killer and is already busy with shifting other people through their zombie, Medium is essential to connecting us to GY and Banshee is required to stay dead to be a useful role.
Contrary to that, the roles optimal to throw me under the bus are: Necro, Banshee, Medium and Zombie.
VD is not optimal since they need to remain fairly hidden.
Necro, imo, is the perfect role because this gains them lit points, and they're less likely to be lynched thanks to that.
Banshee is also fairly a good role to do so because if they're implicated, this allows them to be lynched.
Medium needs to stay alive the longest, and the reasoning for them to implicate me holds the same value as the necro.
Since the VD can also get into the action, they could use the zombie to claim if this is too risky for your tastes.
This is one tactic to be used.
The rest of y'all should be able to use other tactics that you use as wolves since the roles are fairly straightforward.
A note for the Banshee and VD (and myself): Once a banshee possesses a person, the VD needs to prepare so that they can zombify that person to minimise GY info leak.
Also, on odd nights I'll try to grab a killing role to consume the night before to make sure I can kill off the person who was possessed.
We're an intel-tiled team, so we need to focus on disrupting village intel while making more intel available to ourselves.
Medium, in that case, is our hidden ace. They can let us know what intel is being leaked and whether we need to continuously attempt at killing possessed people.
Last game we actively tried avoiding the death of our banshee. But this time, I'll say we should go ahead and utilise every ounce of our abilities.

For tomorrow, hears a basic idea of a plan I have in mind. One of you claims inquisitor/stalker and claims something that makes me look somewhat shady. Maybe the fact that I use WC, or that I visited someone (maybe the VD's target even). The claim is up to your creativity. I'll claim Master's role (he's probably not a vanilla, but I'll send a BH code in case he might be stalker or inquisitor). If anything, this should allow Master to lean towards you and facilitate my lynch.
Uhhhh.... this needs to be highlighted.
1) Darla sends out a BH code to make sure there are no counters from Master.
2) Medium or Necro (or Banshee) claim inquisitor or stalker to implicate me.
3) I counter by claiming another role.
4) Master and the team mate throwing me under the bus facilitate my lynch.
5) Other team members (Banshee, if not implicating me) should try to act like how they do when a team mate is caught so the lynch doesn't feel "rigged".
Naturally, I'd want your suggestions as well.
This is a very simple baseline to work on. If people are not into it, we won't go with it.
